:::summary
Philosophy of religion is the philosophical examination of religious beliefs, practices, and experience. It asks whether belief in God is rational, whether arguments for God's existence succeed, how to reconcile God's goodness with the reality of evil, and how religious language can be meaningful. Standing at the intersection of reason and faith, it is one of the oldest and most vital fields of philosophical inquiry.
:::

